<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-equivalent-vectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Equivalent Vectors</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.9 Vectors 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                    <p>Identify equivalent vectors in different situations</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <li component="lesson-plan">Grade Level: 10</li>
        <li component="lesson-plan">Estimated Duration: 40 minutes</li>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Know</title>
                    <p>The definition of equivalent vectors and the conditions for equivalence (same magnitude and same direction)</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Do</title>
                    <p>Identify and verify equivalent vectors on coordinate grids by checking magnitude and direction</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Apply</title>
                    <p>Use vector equivalence to solve real-world problems involving forces and displacements at different positions</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/equivalent-vectors.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/step-by-step-guide_equivalent-vectors.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <p xml:id="auto_c312st3v">
        Now that you understand how to represent vectors using magnitude and direction, we can explore how to compare them. 
        Is it possible for two vectors to be considered <q><em>equal</em></q> even if they are located in different places on a graph? 
        In this section, you will examine the specific conditions regarding <alert>length</alert> and <alert>direction</alert> that must be met for <alert>two</alert> vectors to be called <alert>equivalent</alert>.
    </p>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Anchor Activity: Discovering Equivalent Vectors</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Organise students into groups of 2–3. Distribute graph paper, rulers, and pencils. Guide students through the activity below.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Circulate among students, ensuring they plot points correctly.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask probing questions: <q>Do the vectors have the same length? Same direction?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For struggling students: <q>Let us measure together. Use your ruler to measure <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> and <m>\mathbf{CD}</m>.</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For early finishers: <q>Draw another vector equivalent to <m>\mathbf{AB}</m>. Can you draw it at a different position?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>Guide students to articulate: <em>Equivalent vectors have the same magnitude and direction.</em></p></li>
                <li><p>Identify 2–3 students with clear findings to share with the class.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Guiding Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li><p>What is the length of vector <m>\mathbf{AB}</m>? What is the length of vector <m>\mathbf{CD}</m>?</p></li>
                <li><p>Do they point in the same direction?</p></li>
                <li><p>Can you slide vector <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> to overlap vector <m>\mathbf{CD}</m> without rotating?</p></li>
                <li><p>Do vectors need to start at the same point to be equivalent?</p></li>
                <li><p>What two properties must vectors share to be equivalent?</p></li>
                <li><p>If you draw a vector from <m>(5,0)</m> to <m>(8,0)</m>, would it be equivalent to <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> and <m>\mathbf{CD}</m>?</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <activity xml:id="auto_gnsuxh6z">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_5zyxwf4q">
            <p xml:id="auto_ufywdslf">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_0s7iqsbq">
                <alert>What you require:</alert> Graph paper,ruler
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_9s6hl1jl">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_uut2oiid">
                    Draw the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> axis on the graph paper.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_wayeekwb">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_89unxyts">
                    Plot the points <m>A(0,4), B(3,4), C(0,2)</m> and <m>D(3,2)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_m8uqhf98">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_iuxbu742">
                    Draw a line to connect point <m>A</m> and <m>B,</m> add an arrow pointing to point <m>B.</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_gv0msy0p">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_6mirgcfx">
                    Draw a line to connect point <m>C</m> and <m>D,</m> add an arrow pointing to point <m>D.</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_qazope1c">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_y88o0kaa">
                    Look at the two arrows you have drawn. Do they look like "clones" (exact copies) of each other?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_w67reupi">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_hrgsarhf">
                    Imagine sliding the vector <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> straight down without turning it.
                    <ul xml:id="auto_rgl3sgm1">
                        <li xml:id="auto_25i20h6y">
                            <p xml:id="auto_cywhtx9t">
                                If you move point <m>A</m> so it sits exactly on top of point <m>C</m>, where does point <m>B</m> land?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_uj8p1lqp">
                            <p xml:id="auto_656x9qm0">
                                Does it land exactly on point <m>D</m>?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_4l1hpnz2">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_uokat6hn">
                    Calculate the length of both vectors and compare the direction they are pointing. 
                    What two properties do vector <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> and vector <m>\mathbf{CD}</m> have in common?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_sewvc2fi">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_u5uzwvgc">
                    Since these vectors share the exact same properties, discuss with your group what relationship exists between them.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <insight xml:id="auto_vksjne4n">
        <p xml:id="auto_dqwftoz6">
            <alert>Two</alert> or <alert>more</alert> vectors are said to be equivalent if they satisfy the following conditions:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_87tx7ag2">
            <ol xml:id="auto_wmf1u5pd" marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_klhjz9ai">
                    <p xml:id="auto_1u0tqa88">
                        They have same <alert>magnitude</alert>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wld20ctk">
                    <p xml:id="auto_26re5lz1">
                        They point in the <alert>same direction</alert>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="equiv-vectors">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="30%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
                <latex-image>  
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Draw parallel lines
                        \draw[thick, -] (0,2) -- (2,2) node[right] {\large $N$};
                        \draw[thick, -] (-2,2) -- (0,2);
                        \node[left] at (-2,2) {\large $M$};
                        
                        \draw[thick, -] (0,0) -- (2,0) node[right] {\large $Q$};
                        \draw[thick, -] (-2,0) -- (0,0);
                        \node[left] at (-2,0) {\large $P$};
                        
                        % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                        \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (-0.2,2) -- (0,2);
                        \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (-0.2,0) -- (0,0);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image> 
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p xml:id="auto_360ym5gh">
            In <xref ref="equiv-vectors"/> above, <m>\textbf{MN} = \textbf{PQ}</m> since they have same direction and equal magnitude.
        </p>
    </insight>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            After students have shared their findings from the anchor activity, formalise the concept of equivalent vectors using the Key Takeaway above.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Important Points to Emphasise:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Equivalent vectors do NOT need to start at the same point.</p></li>
                <li><p>Equivalent vectors do NOT need to end at the same point.</p></li>
                <li><p>Equivalent vectors MUST have the same length (magnitude).</p></li>
                <li><p>Equivalent vectors MUST point in the same direction.</p></li>
                <li><p><alert>Visual Test:</alert> If you can slide one vector (without rotating) so it perfectly overlaps another, they are equivalent.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Misconception</cell>
                    <cell>Clarification</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Equivalent vectors must start at the same point</cell>
                    <cell>No — they can start anywhere on the graph</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Vectors with same magnitude but opposite directions are equivalent</cell>
                    <cell>No — direction must also be the same</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Vectors with same direction but different magnitudes are equivalent</cell>
                    <cell>No — magnitude must also be the same</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Walk students through the worked example below. Encourage them to first check the two conditions (same magnitude and same direction) before concluding equivalence.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Before solving: <q>What two things do we need to check?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>After the example: <q>Is it possible for two vectors to have the same direction but not be equivalent? Why?</q></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <example xml:id="auto_09bzmvj2">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_nldgn0cd">
                Using <xref ref="example-equiv-vect1"/> below, determine whether vector <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> and <m>\mathbf{DC}</m> 
                are equivalent.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="example-equiv-vect1">
                <caption></caption>
                <image width="50%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                            \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-3,-1) grid (3,3);

                            % Draw main grid (original)
                            \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-3,-1) grid (3,3);

                            % Define points for square ABCD in 2nd quadrant
                            \coordinate (A) at (-2,2);
                            \coordinate (B) at (2,2);
                            
                            \coordinate (C) at (2,0);
                            \coordinate (D) at (-2,0);

                            \node[left] at (A) {\small $\mathbf{A}$};
                            \node[right] at (B) {\small $\mathbf{B}$};
                            
                            \node[right] at (C) {\small $\mathbf{C}$};
                            \node[left] at (D) {\small $\mathbf{D}$};

                            % Draw square ABCD
                            \draw[very thick] (A) -- (B);
                            \draw[very thick] (D) -- (C);
                            % \draw[very thick] (A) -- (C);

                            \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (B) -- (0,2) ;
                            \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (C) -- (0,0) ;
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_omx03fsm">
                Vector <m>\mathbf{AB} \text{ and } \mathbf{DC}</m> 
                are equivalent because they have the same magnitude, 
                <m>|\mathbf{AB}| = |\mathbf{DC}| </m>, and they point in the same 
                direction
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment (5 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Exit Ticket</alert> — Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li><p>Define equivalent vectors in your own words.</p></li>
                <li><p>Draw two equivalent vectors on a coordinate plane that start at different points.</p></li>
                <li><p>Are vectors from <m>A(1,2)</m> to <m>B(4,6)</m> and from <m>C(0,0)</m> to <m>D(3,4)</m> equivalent? Explain.</p></li>
                <li><p>Can two vectors have the same magnitude but not be equivalent? Give an example.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li><p>Equivalent vectors have the same magnitude and direction, but can start at different positions.</p></li>
                <li><p>Example: Vector from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(2,3)</m> and vector from <m>(5,5)</m> to <m>(7,8)</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Yes. Both have magnitude <m>5</m> and point in the same direction (<m>3</m> right, <m>4</m> up).</p></li>
                <li><p>Yes. Vectors <m>\binom{2}{0}</m> and <m>\binom{0}{2}</m> both have magnitude <m>2</m> but point in different directions.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-equivalent-vectors">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_00198uni">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_c76o954o">
                    Is it possible for two vectors to have the same 
                    direction but <alert>not</alert> to be equivalent? Explain your answer.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <alert>Yes</alert>. Two vectors are only equivalent if they have both the <alert>same direction</alert> and the <alert>same magnitude</alert> (length).
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_e4t6o20e">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_at9khsn0">
                    In <xref ref="exercises-equiv-vector-1"/>, 
                    identify pairs of <alert>equivalent</alert> vectors 
                    and <alert>non-equivalent</alert> vectors. 
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="exercises-equiv-vector-1">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image width="40%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}

                                % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                                \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-3,-3) grid (3,3);

                                % Draw main grid (original)
                                \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-3,-3) grid (3,3);

                                % Define points for square ABCD in 2nd quadrant
                                \coordinate (A) at (-2,2);
                                \coordinate (B) at (2,2);
                                \coordinate (C) at (2,-2);
                                \coordinate (D) at (-2,-2);

                                \node[above left] at (A) {\small $\mathbf{A}$};
                                \node[above right] at (B) {\small $\mathbf{B}$};
                                \node[below right] at (C) {\small $\mathbf{C}$};
                                \node[below left] at (D) {\small $\mathbf{D}$};

                                % Draw square ABCD
                                \draw[very thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                                \draw[very thick] (D) -- (B);
                                \draw[very thick] (A) -- (C);

                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (D) -- (-2,0) ;
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (D) -- (0,-2) ;
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (C) -- (2,0) ;
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (B) -- (0,2) ;

                                %diagonals
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (D) -- (-0.2,-0.2) ;
                                \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (C) -- (0.2,-0.2) ;

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Equivalent Pairs
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\overrightarrow{DA}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{CB}</m>: Both point directly upward and have the same length (sides of the square).
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\overrightarrow{DC}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>: Both point directly to the right and have the same length.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\overrightarrow{DO}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{OB}</m> Both point in the same direction along the diagonal and have the same length.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Non-Equivalent Pairs
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\overrightarrow{DA}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{BC}</m>: While they have the same length, they point in opposite directions (up vs. down).
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\overrightarrow{DC}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{DA}</m>: These have the same length but different directions (horizontal vs. vertical).
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\overrightarrow{DB}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m>: These are the diagonals; they have the same length but different directions.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_b2tri8nw">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_zb0fgj6x">
                    Draw two vectors that have the same magnitude and direction but start at different points.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="equiv-vectors-1">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                           \begin{tikzpicture}

                                % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                                \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-1,-1) grid (6,5);

                                % Draw main grid
                                \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-1,-1) grid (6,5);
                                
                                % Draw Axes
                                \draw[thick, -&gt;] (-1,0) -- (6.5,0) node[below] {$x$};
                                \draw[thick, -&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,5.5) node[left] {$y$};

                                % Define vector 1 starting at (1,1)
                                \coordinate (Start1) at (1,1);
                                \coordinate (End1) at (4,3); % Magnitude: sqrt(3^2 + 2^2)
                                
                                % Define vector 2 starting at (2,0)
                                \coordinate (Start2) at (2,0);
                                \coordinate (End2) at (5,2); % Same magnitude and direction
                                
                                % Draw Vector 1 (Blue)
                                \draw[very thick, blue, -{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (Start1) -- (End1) 
                                    node[midway, above left] {$\mathbf{u}$};
                                \fill (Start1) circle (2pt);
                                \node[below left] at (Start1) {\small $(1,1)$};

                                % Draw Vector 2 (Red)
                                \draw[very thick, red, -{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (Start2) -- (End2) 
                                    node[midway, below right] {$\mathbf{v}$};
                                \fill (Start2) circle (2pt);
                                \node[below right] at (Start2) {\small $(2,0)$};

                                % Label note
                                \node[draw, fill=white, font=\small] at (3,4.5) {$\mathbf{u} = \mathbf{v} = \binom{3}{2}$};

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Provide pre-drawn vectors with labelled magnitudes and directions.</p></li>
                <li><p>Use colour coding: same colour for equivalent vectors.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide tracing paper to physically slide vectors and check overlap.</p></li>
                <li><p>Start with horizontal and vertical vectors only.</p></li>
                <li><p>Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Encourage students to create their own equivalent vector problems.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask students to explain why position does not matter for equivalence.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide mixed practice with diagonal vectors.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Explore equivalent vectors in three dimensions.</p></li>
                <li><p>Investigate how equivalent vectors relate to parallel lines.</p></li>
                <li><p>Challenge: Prove that if two vectors are equivalent, their components are equal.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity: Real-World Application — Forces in Physics</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Work in pairs or small groups. Situation: Two people push a car with the same force in the same direction, but at different locations on the car. Draw force vectors for each person and determine whether they are equivalent. Discuss what the total force on the car would be.
        </p>
    </axiom>


